  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- These establish global standards and principles for combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Frameworks\n- Countries adapt their national laws to comply with international standards\n- Standardized definitions of money laundering offenses\n- Consistent requirements for financial institutions' reporting and due diligence\n\n3. Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering prosecutions\n\n4. Regulatory Compliance\n- International banks must follow global anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines\n- Cross-border financial transactions subject to international scrutiny\n- Sanctions for non-compliance with international regulations\n\n5. Enforcement Coordination\n- Joint investigations across jurisdictions\n- Shared databases and intelligence\n- Coordinated asset seizure and recovery efforts\n\n6. Technological Considerations\n- Addressing challenges of digital currencies\n- Developing consistent approaches to emerging financial technologies\n- Collaborative approaches to cybercrime and financial fraud\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
